  "prompt": "Household income $280K and able to pay $130K down payment, can I buy a house in San Francisco?",
  "response": "Based on your household income of $280,000 and a down payment of $130,000, you should have a good chance of being able to buy a house in San Francisco, but there are several factors to consider:\n\n1. **Housing Prices**: The median home price in San Francisco is quite high, often exceeding $1 million. As of my last data in October 2023, it could vary, so checking current market listings is advisable.\n\n2. **Loan Amount and Mortgage**: With a $130,000 down payment, if you were to buy a home priced at, say, $1 million, you\u2019d be looking at a loan of $870,000. Lenders typically use the debt-to-income ratio (DTI) to determine loan eligibility.\n\n3. **Debt-to-Income Ratio**: Lenders generally prefer a DTI ratio below 43%. With an income of $280,000 (approximately $23,333/month), your allowable monthly debt payment would be around $10,000. This would include your potential mortgage payment, property taxes, insurance, and any other debt obligations.\n\n4. **Mortgage Payment**: If we assume an interest rate and a 30-year fixed mortgage, you\u2019d need to calculate what your monthly payment would be on an $870,000 loan. For example, at a 6.5% interest rate, the monthly principal and interest payment would be around $5,500. Add in property taxes (~1.2% annually) and insurance, which could bring your total monthly payment to about $7,000 - $8,000.\n\n5. **Affordability**: If your projected monthly housing payments would fit within the DTI guidelines based on your income, then yes, you could potentially buy a house. However, if your total monthly payments exceed your budget or the DTI ratio, you might need to adjust expectations, consider less expensive properties, or save a larger down payment.\n\n6. **Additional Costs**: Don't forget to factor in closing costs, maintenance, and other expenses that come with homeownership.\n\n7. **Pre-Approval**: It would be prudent to get pre-approved for a mortgage to see how much you can borrow and at what interest rate, which will give you a clearer picture of your purchasing power.\n\nIn summary, while it seems feasible to purchase a house in San Francisco with your income and down payment, it\u2019s important to consider the specific prices, market conditions, and financial commitments associated with homeownership.",
